    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "To better understand the dataset, a subset of images from the training data was visualized. This helps verify that the images are correctly labeled and shows more into the diversity and characteristics of each class. By plotting a grid of sample images along with their labels, it becomes easier to observe differences between categories like buildings, forest, glacier, mountain, sea, and street. This was an important preliminary step, as it made sure that the dataset was correctly loaded and gives more understanding of the classification task before training any models."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "K3XTIIIHvpeN"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# normalize data\n",
        "# rescale pixel values [0, 255] to [0, 1] improve training stability\n",
        "train_data = train_data.map(lambda x, y: (tf.cast(x, tf.float32) / 255.0, y))\n",
        "val_data = val_data.map(lambda x, y: (tf.cast(x, tf.float32) / 255.0, y))\n",
        "test_data = test_data.map(lambda x, y: (tf.cast(x, tf.float32) / 255.0, y))"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "wgHZ4AQTvt0L"
      },
      "execution_count": 11,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 12,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "OU8qHXCohqmO"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# CNN model\n",
        "# Model uses stack of Conv2D + MaxPooling layers to extract features\n",
        "# followed by Dense layers for classification\n",
        "\n",
        "model = models.Sequential([\n",
        "  layers.Input(shape=(150,150,3)),\n",
        "\n",
        "  # feature extraction - increase filters to capture more complex patterns\n",
        "  layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu'), # detects simple features - edges\n",
        "  layers.MaxPooling2D(), # reduces spatial size\n",
        "\n",
        "  layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu'), # detects more complex patterns\n",
        "  layers.MaxPooling2D(),\n",
        "\n",
        "  layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu'), # high-level features\n",
        "  layers.MaxPooling2D(),\n",
        "\n",
        "  # classification\n",
        "  layers.Flatten(), # convert feature maps  to vector\n",
        "  layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'), # fully connected layer\n",
        "  layers.Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax') # output layer for 6 classes\n",
        "])"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "FRdSNUrWoK5O"
      },
      "source": [
        "The CNN uses three convolutional layers with 32, 64, and 128 filters. The first layer detects low-level features such as edges, corners, and simple textures. The second layer captures intermediate patterns like shapes, repeated textures, and object parts. The third layer extracts high-level features specific to each class, such as the structure of buildings, tree canopies, snow patterns on glaciers, or road layouts in street scenes. Each convolutional layer is followed by a max-pooling layer that reduces the spatial dimensions of the feature maps, keeps the strongest activations, decreases the number of parameters, and introduces translational invariance.\n",
        "\n",
        "The feature maps from the final convolutional layer are flattened into a one-dimensional vector and passed through fully connected dense layers. These dense layers combine the spatial features into class-specific representations, producing outputs for the six categories in the dataset. ReLU activation is used in convolutional and dense layers to introduce non-linearity, and softmax is applied in the final layer to output class probabilities. The increasing number of filters allows the network to represent more complex patterns deeper in the network, while pooling prevents overfitting and reduces computation.",
        "\n"
        "The architecture uses three convolutional layers to balance model complexity and performance. Too few layers would limit feature extraction, while too many could lead to overfitting given the dataset size. Increasing the number of filters (32, 64, 128) allows the model to learn progressively more complex features. MaxPooling is used after each convolution to reduce spatial dimensions and improve computational efficiency."
      ]
    },
