        "The original CNN achieved about 78% accuracy. Precision, recall, and F1-scores were relatively balanced across most classes, and performance was strong and consistent, especially on the forest category. The results were fairly even across the dataset. The ResNet50 model achieved about 65% accuracy, but performance was uneven across classes. The mountain category had very low recall. This model showed poor generalization and difficulty distinguishing certain categories. The augmented CNN achieved about 70% accuracy. Its performance was more balanced across classes than ResNet50, but overall accuracy remained lower than that of the original CNN.\n",
        "\n",
        "The original CNN was well-suited to the dataset, learning features directly from the data without being overly complex. ResNet50, on the other hand, was a deeper pre-trained model that may not have been fully fine-tuned. It likely required more data and additional training to adapt effectively to this dataset, and its complexity made optimization more challenging on smaller datasets. The augmented CNN introduced more varied training data, which helped reduce overfitting, but it did not surpass the original CNN, possibly because the original architecture was already optimized for this task. Visually similar categories, such as mountain, glacier, and sea, showed weaknesses across all models. The original CNN handled these classes more consistently, while ResNet50 showed larger weaknesses. The augmented CNN improved balance across these classes but did not increase overall accuracy.\n",
